---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = "How to Run a Discovery Bible Study | RK Castillo";
const description = "Learn discovery bible study how to facilitate one effectively. A step-by-step guide to leading DBS groups that transform lives and multiply through obedience-based learning.";

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a Discovery Bible Study?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Discovery Bible Study (DBS) is a simple, reproducible method of studying Scripture where a small group reads a passage together, discusses what it says about God and people, and commits to obeying what they've learned and sharing it with others. It's designed so that anyone can facilitate it without formal theological training."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How many people should be in a Discovery Bible Study group?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Discovery Bible Study works best with 3 to 12 people. Smaller groups allow for deeper sharing and accountability, while groups larger than 12 can make it difficult for everyone to participate meaningfully. If a group grows beyond 12, consider multiplying into two groups."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need to be a Bible expert to lead a Discovery Bible Study?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No, you do not need to be a Bible expert. The DBS method is designed so that the facilitator guides the process rather than teaches content. The Holy Spirit is the teacher. The facilitator simply asks the questions and keeps the group focused on the passage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long does a Discovery Bible Study session take?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A typical Discovery Bible Study session takes between 60 to 90 minutes. This includes time for checking in on previous commitments, reading the passage, discussing the questions, and making new commitments to obey and share."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What passages should I use for a Discovery Bible Study?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Many DBS practitioners use a curated list of passages that tell the story of God from creation through the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus. Common starting points include Genesis 1, Genesis 3, Luke 15, and John 3. The key is choosing passages that reveal God's character and invite a response of obedience."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a Discovery Bible Study be done with people who aren't yet believers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely. Discovery Bible Study is one of the most effective methods for engaging people who are not yet followers of Jesus. Because it lets the Scripture speak for itself and doesn't require prior knowledge, it creates a safe space for seekers to encounter God's Word directly."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <main style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1rem;">
    <article>
      <h1 style="color: #1A1A2E; font-size: 2.2rem; line-height: 1.3; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        How to Run a Discovery Bible Study: A Complete Guide
      </h1>

      <p style="font-size: 1.15rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        If you're looking for a <strong>discovery bible study how to</strong> guide, the process is remarkably simple: gather a small group, read a short Scripture passage together, and ask a set of reproducible questions that lead to obedience and sharing. Discovery Bible Study (DBS) is one of the most effective and reproducible methods for studying Scripture in a way that transforms lives and naturally multiplies groups of committed followers of Jesus.
      </p>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Unlike traditional Bible studies where an expert teaches and others listen, DBS puts the Word of God at the center and the Holy Spirit in the role of teacher. The facilitator doesn't lecture — they guide. This means anyone, regardless of education or theological background, can lead a group. And that's precisely what makes it so powerful for kingdom multiplication.
      </p>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        What Is a Discovery Bible Study?
      </h2>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        A Discovery Bible Study is a small-group Bible study method designed for simplicity and reproducibility. It originated from church planting movements around the world and has been used to catalyze movements of obedient followers of Jesus on every continent. The method centers on a consistent set of questions applied to any Scripture passage, making it easy to learn, easy to remember, and easy to pass on.
      </p>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        The genius of DBS is that it builds two habits that are essential for spiritual growth and multiplication: <strong>obedience</strong> to what Scripture says and <strong>sharing</strong> what you've learned with others. These two commitments are what distinguish DBS from a typical study group and what give it the potential to multiply exponentially.
      </p>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        How Do You Facilitate a Discovery Bible Study Step by Step?
      </h2>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Here is the step-by-step process for running a DBS session:
      </p>

      <h3 style="color: #1A1A2E; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
        1. Check In (10–15 minutes)
      </h3>
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Begin each session by asking two accountability questions from the previous week: <em>"How did you obey what you learned last week?"</em> and <em>"Who did you share it with?"</em> This isn't about guilt or pressure — it's about building a culture of follow-through. If someone didn't follow through, simply encourage them and move on. These questions reinforce that Bible study isn't merely academic; it's meant to change how we live and to spread.
      </p>

      <h3 style="color: #1A1A2E; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
        2. Read the Passage (10 minutes)
      </h3>
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Choose a short passage — typically 10 to 25 verses. Have someone read it aloud. Then have another person retell it in their own words from memory. Others in the group can fill in anything that was missed. This retelling step is critical because it ensures everyone understands the text and practices internalizing Scripture rather than just passively hearing it.
      </p>

      <h3 style="color: #1A1A2E; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
        3. Discuss the Discovery Questions (25–35 minutes)
      </h3>
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Ask these three questions and let the group discuss:
      </p>
      <ul style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
        <li><strong>"What does this passage tell us about God?"</strong> — This keeps the focus on God's character, His nature, His promises, and His actions.</li>
        <li><strong>"What does this passage tell us about people?"</strong> — This helps the group see human nature, our need, our failures, and our role in God's story.</li>
        <li><strong>"If this is true, what do we need to change or obey?"</strong> — This is the application question. It moves the study from information to transformation.</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        As a facilitator, your role is to keep pointing people back to the text. If someone shares an opinion that isn't rooted in the passage, gently ask, <em>"Where do you see that in the passage?"</em> This trains the group to let Scripture speak for itself.
      </p>

      <h3 style="color: #1A1A2E; font-size: 1.3rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
        4. Commit to Obey and Share (10 minutes)
      </h3>
      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        End the session by asking each person to make a specific, actionable commitment: <em>"What will you do this week to obey what you've learned?"</em> and <em>"Who will you share this with before we meet again?"</em> These commitments are what drive multiplication. When people share what they've learned, new groups can form organically.
      </p>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Why Does Discovery Bible Study Work So Well?
      </h2>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        DBS works because it aligns with how Jesus trained His followers. Jesus didn't set up lecture halls — He gathered small groups, taught through stories and questions, and sent people out to obey and share immediately. DBS mirrors this pattern. It removes the bottleneck of requiring trained leaders, because the method itself is the training. Anyone who has participated in a few sessions can turn around and facilitate one for others.
      </p>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        The emphasis on obedience over knowledge is also transformative. Many people in traditional church settings accumulate tremendous Bible knowledge without corresponding life change. DBS flips this by making obedience the measure of growth, not information retention. When a person obeys even a small portion of what they've read, their faith deepens in ways that hours of passive listening never could.
      </p>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Can You Use DBS With People Who Don't Follow Jesus Yet?
      </h2>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Yes — and this is one of its greatest strengths. Discovery Bible Study is an incredibly effective tool for engaging seekers, skeptics, and people from other worldviews. Because the facilitator doesn't preach or lecture, there's no pressure. Participants simply engage with the text and discover what it says for themselves. Many people who would never walk into a church building will sit in a living room or coffee shop and explore Scripture through DBS.
      </p>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        When using DBS with not-yet-believers, it's common to start with a set of "Creation to Christ" passages that walk through the grand narrative of Scripture. This allows people to encounter God progressively and come to faith through their own discovery rather than someone else's persuasion.
      </p>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        What Are Common Mistakes to Avoid in DBS?
      </h2>

      <ul style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
        <li><strong>Teaching instead of facilitating.</strong> The moment you start explaining the passage, you've turned it into a traditional Bible study. Trust the Holy Spirit to illuminate the text.</li>
        <li><strong>Skipping the accountability questions.</strong> The check-in at the beginning is not optional — it's the engine of transformation and multiplication.</li>
        <li><strong>Choosing passages that are too long.</strong> Keep it short enough that the group can retell it from memory. If the passage is too long, people disengage.</li>
        <li><strong>Allowing discussion to drift away from the text.</strong> Always bring it back to the passage. The authority is Scripture, not opinions.</li>
        <li><strong>Not modeling obedience yourself.</strong> If the facilitator isn't obeying and sharing, why would anyone else?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="color: #1170C3; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        How Does DBS Lead to Multiplication?
      </h2>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        Every DBS session ends with the commitment to share what was learned. When a participant shares with a friend, family member, or coworker and that person shows interest, a new group can be started. Because the method is so simple, the person who was just a participant last month can be a facilitator this month. This creates an exponential growth pattern where groups multiply naturally without requiring institutional infrastructure or professional clergy.
      </p>

      <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #333; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        This is how movements happen. Not through programs, but through people who obey Scripture and share it with others who do the same. DBS is not just a method — it's a lifestyle of discovery, obedience, and multiplication.
      </p>

